file-name: XC522278-Pacific Swallow-call-1-3-Xeno-Kledang-Sayong Forest Reserve, Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia-23rd January 2020.mp3
rmk: I was watching a pair of Pacific Swallows that I know fairly well. They were hawking insects, using a stationary ceiling fan as a vantage position, and calling out intermittently. Most calls were soft ‘wep’ or ‘kwek’ (Wells 2007) that needed a good mike to pick up. I decided to try a closer approach for images and one bird gave out a ‘steam-whistle’ call (Wells 2007) and they flew off. This call appeared to be a warning call. I tested this when they returned shortly and played it back; they immediately flew off. Wells says this ‘steam-whistle’ call is used to signal the presence of a predator near nest. The first few calls in the recording are contact calls (soft ‘wep’ or ‘kwek’) and the recording ends with a ‘steam-whistle’ call.
The pacific swallow was on an overhead telephone wire.
